olive oil
2 potato
½ tin sweetcorn
1 clove garlic
1 tomato
1 cucumber
5 g coriander
1 bunch spring onion
1 packet pork mince
½ packet fine breadcrumbs
1 egg
1 packet sour cream
1 packet Shredded Cheddar Cheese
1 sachet Tex-Mex spice blend
½ tsp vinegar (white wine or red wine)

Preheat the oven to 240°C/220°C fan-forced. Cut the potato into fries, then place on a lined oven tray. Drizzle with olive oil and season with salt. Toss to coat, spread out evenly, then bake for 20 minutes. Remove the tray from the oven, sprinkle over the shredded Cheddar cheese, then bake until melted and golden, a further 5 minutes.

While the fries are baking, drain the sweetcorn (see ingredients). Finely chop the garlic. Heat a large frying pan over a high heat. When the pan is hot, cook the sweetcorn until lightly charred, 4-5 minutes. Transfer to a medium bowl. Roughly chop the tomato and cucumber. Roughly chop the coriander. Thinly slice the spring onion.

TIP: Cover the pan with a lid if the corn kernels are "popping" out.

In a large bowl, add the pork mince, Tex-Mex spice blend, fine breadcrumbs (see ingredients), garlic and the egg. Season with salt and pepper and mix well to combine. Using damp hands, form heaped spoonfuls of the pork mixture into meatballs, then flatten to make 2cm-thick rissoles and transfer to a plate. You should get 4-5 rissoles per person.

Return the frying pan to a medium-high heat with a drizzle of olive oil. Cook the pork rissoles in batches until browned and cooked through, 4-5 minutes each side. Transfer to a plate.

While the rissoles are cooking, combine the sour
cream and 1/2 the spring onion in a small bowl.
Set aside. To the bowl with the charred corn, add
the tomato, cucumber, the vinegar, coriander, a
drizzle of olive oil and the remaining spring onion.
Season and stir to combine.

Divide the Tex-Mex pork rissoles, cheesy fries and charred corn salsa between plates. Dollop with the spring onion sour cream to serve.